06574nam a22008055i 9789048554034DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485540347 a10.1515/97890485540342doi  a(DE-B1597)651595  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aD107.9 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a929.7094223/eng/2023050800aDynasties and State Formation in Early Modern Europe /ced. by Harald Gustafsson, Liesbeth Geevers. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Court Studies00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- t1. Building Dynasties, Shaping States : Dynasty and State Formation in Early Modern Europe -- t2. Divine Right of Dynasty : Deposing the God-Given Monarch in Protestant Europe -- t3. Presence Makes the Heart Grow Fonder : Proximity and the Creation of Dynasty -- t4. The Austrian Nephews : The Offspring of Maximilian II and Maria of Austria at the Service of the Spanish King -- t5. Sixteen Corpses : The First Reburials in the Escorial in 1586 and the Dynastic Dynamics that Made Them Happen -- t6. An Elected Dynasty of Sweden? Blood, Charisma and Representative Monarchy -- t7. Narrowing Dynastic Rule : Models of Governance, Social Conflict and the Hobbesian Bargain in Early Modern Sweden (1560-1718) -- t8. The Nassaus and State Formation in Pre-Modern Germany -- t9. Dynastic Marriage Spheres in Early Modern Europe : A Comparison of the Danish Oldenburgs and Three Houses of the Empire -- t10. The Frustrations of Being the Spare : Second Sons in the French Monarchy and their Increasingly Limited Roles in Politics and Society, 1560s-1780s -- t11. Danish Dynastic Histories in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries : Claus Christoffersen Lyschander, Vitus Bering, Ludvig Holberg and Hans Peter Anchersen -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn state formation research, princely houses have been a blind spot. The development of states has been discussed from many perspectives, like interstate competition, internal social conflicts, fiscal-military developments, etc., but at the centre of most European states, there was a princely house. These ruling houses have been overlooked in studies about state formation. What's more, when discussing such dynasties, the vertical chronological perspective (grandfather-father-son) is all dominating, for instance in the focus on dynastic continuity, dynastic culture and representation, and the like. This collection of essays highlights the horizontal perspective (ruler, all children, siblings, cousins), in asking how the members of a princely family acted as a power network. The quest is to develop an understanding how this family network interplayed with other factors in the state formation process. This volume brings together existing knowledge of the topic with the aim of exchanging insights and furthering knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMonarchyzEuropexHistory. 0aRoyal houseszEuropexHistory. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aState Formation, Dynasties, Conglomerate States.1 aGeevers, Liesbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeevers, Liesbeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGonzález Cuerva, Rubén, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafsson, Harald, econtributor.